<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="type material">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Type material.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Holotype, female, 5 mm (with oostegite buds), USNM 282716. Paratypes: 1 male, 5.4 mm, USNM 282717; 1 male AM P.45339.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="type locality">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Type locality.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Gulf of Mexico, south of Mobile Bay (approximately 
<geoCoordinate degrees="29" direction="north" minutes="12" orientation="latitude" precision="925" value="29.2">29°12'N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate degrees="85" direction="west" minutes="07" orientation="longitude" precision="925" value="-85.11667">85°07'W</geoCoordinate>
), from stomach of a Blackfin grenadier, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Goode &amp; Bean" baseAuthorityYear="1885" class="Actinopterygii" family="Macrouridae" genus="Coelorinchus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Coelorinchus caribbaeus" order="Gadiformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="caribbaeus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Coelorinchus caribbaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Goode &amp; Bean, 1885), 200 m depth.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="depth range">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Depth range.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
95-200 m (
<bibRefCitation author="Lowry, JK" journalOrPublisher="Memoirs of the Hourglass Cruises" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="1 - 148" refId="B129" refString="Lowry, JK, Stoddart, HE, 1997. Amphipoda Crustacea IV. Families Aristiidae, Cyphocarididae, Endevouridae, Lysianassidae, Scopelocheiridae, Uristidae. Memoirs of the Hourglass Cruises 10: 1 - 148" title="Amphipoda Crustacea IV. Families Aristiidae, Cyphocarididae, Endevouridae, Lysianassidae, Scopelocheiridae, Uristidae." volume="10" year="1997">Lowry and Stoddart 1997</bibRefCitation>
). The deeper record represents animals taken from fish stomachs.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
